The Riemann zeta function $\zeta(s)$ has a derivative $\zeta'(s)$. At $s = -2n$, where $n > 0$, we need to show $\zeta'(-2n) \neq 0$.

We can use the fact that the zeta function has simple zeros at the negative even integers. A simple zero means that $\zeta(s)$ can be written as $(s + 2n) \cdot f(s)$ where $f(s)$ is non-zero at $s = -2n$. Then the derivative would be $(s + 2n) \cdot f'(s) + f(s) \cdot 1$, which at $s = -2n$ would be $0 \cdot f'(-2n) + f(-2n) \cdot 1 = f(-2n) \neq 0$.

